246ctt-0002ctt-0002.xmlCubical Type TheoryDefinition2024823Trey Plante
Cubical type theory is a constructive approach to homotopy type theory..248ctt-0001ctt-0001.xmlPartial ElementsDefinition2024823Trey Plante
Partial elements are elements of a type that are defined on the extent of a cofibration formula. Partial elements are used in cubical type theory
to describe partially specified n-dimensional cubes.
I use the notation  [\alpha ] \rightarrow  A  for the type
of partial elements of A defined on  \alpha  .  Partial elements internalize the structure of the judgement  \alpha  \vdash  a : A.
The typing rules for partial elements are as follows:
    \usepackage {ebproof}
    \usepackage {mathtools}

    \begin {prooftree}
        \hypo {\Gamma  \vdash  A : Type_{l}}
        \infer 1[form]{\Gamma  \vdash  [\alpha ] \to  A}
    \end {prooftree}
    \quad 
    \begin {prooftree}
        \hypo {\Gamma  ,\alpha  \vdash  a : A}
        \infer 1[intro]{\Gamma  \vdash  in(f) : [\alpha ] \to  A}
    \end {prooftree}


    \usepackage {ebproof}
    \usepackage {mathtools}

    \begin {prooftree}
        \hypo {\Gamma  \vdash  f : [\alpha ] \to  A}
        \infer 1[elim]{\Gamma  \vdash  out(f) : A}
    \end {prooftree}
    \quad 
    \begin {prooftree}
        \hypo {\Gamma  \vdash  f : [\alpha ] \to  A}
        \infer 1[comp]{\Gamma  \vdash  out(f) \equiv  a}
    \end {prooftree}
250ctt-0003ctt-0003.xmlBoundary TypesDefinition2024828Trey Plante
A boundary type is a type that describes the witness of a partial element being ``extensible''.
  Given a partial element u : [\alpha ] \to  A, the boundary type A[\alpha  \to  u] is the type of elements a : A that ``extend'' u. A term a : A[\alpha  \to  u] is a proof that a : A and u : A agree on \alpha .
  Any term u : A is a term of A[\alpha  \to  u] because u is equivalent with itself. Thus, the boundary type internalizes two judgments: \Gamma  \vdash  a : A and \Gamma , \alpha  \vdash  a \equiv  u : A.
  Boundary types can be thought of as a \Sigma -type: \Sigma  (a : A) ([\phi ] \to  A \equiv  u).
